operate in a national context focused on immigration enforcement rather than immigrant integration. In Making Immigrant Rights Real, Els de Graauw examines how immigrant-serving nonprofits can make impressive policy gains despite these limitations.Drawing on three case studies of immigrant rights policies—language access, labor rights, and municipal ID cards—in San Francisco, de Graauw develops a tripartite model of advocacy strategies that nonprofits have used to propose, enact, and implement immigrant-friendly policies: administrative advocacy, cross-sectoral and cross-organizational collaborations, and strategic issue framing. The inventive development and deployment of these strategies enabled immigrant-serving nonprofits in San Francisco to secure some remarkable new immigrant rights victories, and de Graauw explores how other cities can learn from their experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImmigrantsxCivil rightszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aImmigrantsxServices forzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aNonprofit organizationsxPolitical activityzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aSocial integrationxPolitical aspectszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aimmigrant nonprofits, city politics, program implementation, immigrant rights policies, advocacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170349240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97815017